00:37:04.260 --> 00:37:08.390
Second theme, science in Islam.

00:37:08.390 --> 00:37:13.030
Again the popular imagination,
well education is

00:37:13.030 --> 00:37:15.060
in crisis in the Middle East.

00:37:15.060 --> 00:37:22.190 position:56%
A report issued in 2015, showed
that although Muslim populations are

00:37:22.190 --> 00:37:24.300 position:56%
about 25% of the world's population,

00:37:24.300 --> 00:37:28.270
the majority of Muslim
populations produce about 6%

00:37:28.270 --> 00:37:29.690
of the worlds published research.

00:37:29.690 --> 00:37:31.970
Of course there are all
sorts of reasons for that,

00:37:31.970 --> 00:37:35.770
but in the popular imagination
there is an incompatibility

00:37:35.770 --> 00:37:41.420
between the irrationality
of Islam and science.

00:37:42.840 --> 00:37:46.530
My answer to that, Biruni.

00:37:46.530 --> 00:37:51.900
Biruni is an extraordinary
figure of 11th century learning.

00:37:51.900 --> 00:37:54.930
He was a genuine polymath.

00:37:54.930 --> 00:37:58.190
We tend to use the word
a little bit recklessly.

00:37:58.190 --> 00:38:02.340
In Biruni's case he was a polymath.

00:38:02.340 --> 00:38:05.630
He was born in what
is now Uzbekistan,

00:38:05.630 --> 00:38:11.390
he appeared to have been
something of a prodigy as a child,

00:38:11.390 --> 00:38:20.220
studied music, but by the time
he was advancing towards higher

00:38:20.220 --> 00:38:25.680
education, it became clear that
he had very significant talents

00:38:25.680 --> 00:38:28.660
in the exact sciences, mathematics.

00:38:28.660 --> 00:38:36.030
By the age of 20, he was observing
the summer solstice and deducing

00:38:36.030 --> 00:38:41.880
from observations, a number
of astronomical facts.

00:38:41.880 --> 00:38:48.970
He was a very mean theoretical
as well as an applied physicist.

00:38:48.970 --> 00:38:54.550
He was as I said, a quite
extraordinary mathematician.

00:38:57.180 --> 00:39:08.450
He commanded the full
spectrum of the sciences,

00:39:08.450 --> 00:39:12.710
a term used in Islamic learning
to denote disciplined bodies

00:39:12.710 --> 00:39:18.660
of knowledge in ways that
nowadays is hard to fathom.

00:39:18.660 --> 00:39:22.780
I mean the closest one would
find would be a Voltaire,

00:39:22.780 --> 00:39:26.720
the person who's operating
across that full spectrum

00:39:26.720 --> 00:39:31.570
of knowledge before what CP Snow
infamously called the two cultures,

00:39:31.570 --> 00:39:36.330 position:56%
humanities, the division between
humanities and the sciences emerged.

00:39:36.330 --> 00:39:42.010
In addition to his
extraordinary feats applied

00:39:42.010 --> 00:39:46.850
in theoretical science, he
also was a prodigious historian

00:39:46.850 --> 00:39:48.820
who wrote arguably one

00:39:48.820 --> 00:39:51.790
of the earliest works
of comparative history.

00:39:51.790 --> 00:39:55.760
And at the same time, and this
is why one of the respects

00:39:55.760 --> 00:39:59.960
in which he's so interesting,
he was born in Uzbekistan,

00:39:59.960 --> 00:40:02.850
but he was patronized by what's
called the Ghaznavid dynasty,

00:40:02.850 --> 00:40:08.340
and the Ghaznavids were a dynasty
that ruled from Afghanistan,

00:40:08.340 --> 00:40:14.800
and waged war, at least for the
first 20 years almost ceaselessly

00:40:14.800 --> 00:40:17.450
in what is now India
on the subcontinent.

00:40:17.450 --> 00:40:21.540
And Biruni followed
those campaigning armies,

00:40:21.540 --> 00:40:24.680
sucking up Indian learning.

00:40:24.680 --> 00:40:29.520
Biruni had not only Arabic,
and Persian, and some Greek,

00:40:29.520 --> 00:40:36.890
and some Hebrew, and some
Syriac, he also learned Sanskrit.

00:40:36.890 --> 00:40:41.240
So, in addition to being this
extraordinary exact scientist,

00:40:41.240 --> 00:40:44.220
he was a very mean
historian as well,

00:40:44.220 --> 00:40:48.570
and he certainly wrote what I
would feel comfortable describing

00:40:48.570 --> 00:40:51.700
as the world's first work
of comparative religion,

00:40:51.700 --> 00:40:56.270
a book on India in which he
conceptualizes religious traditions

00:40:56.270 --> 00:41:00.610
and compares them to each
other- an Indian tradition,

00:41:00.610 --> 00:41:04.020
a Jewish tradition, a Christian
tradition, an Islamic tradition.

00:41:04.020 --> 00:41:06.580
There's really nothing else
like it, and he's operating

00:41:06.580 --> 00:41:09.680
in the 11th century,
quite extraordinary.

00:41:13.130 --> 00:41:14.740
Islam and capitalism.

00:41:14.740 --> 00:41:17.690 position:56%
This is another one of my favorites.

00:41:17.690 --> 00:41:21.550
Capitalism is retarded one
reads in the Islamic world,

00:41:21.550 --> 00:41:25.400
either because of Sharia
, or because of politics,

00:41:25.400 --> 00:41:32.620
inheritance law, the relative
weakness of partnerships,

00:41:32.620 --> 00:41:34.980
impossibility of joint
stock companies,

00:41:34.980 --> 00:41:40.020
endowments that alienate capital
from investment, tax evasion.

00:41:40.020 --> 00:41:43.020
There are a whole range of cultural

00:41:43.020 --> 00:41:51.160
and religious reasons given why
Islamic economies don't prosper the

00:41:51.160 --> 00:41:56.800
way they should, or so we read.

00:41:56.800 --> 00:42:07.790
Abu al-Qasim Ramisht
belongs to the 12th century.

00:42:08.920 --> 00:42:17.620
He was from what's now South
West Iran on the coast.

00:42:17.620 --> 00:42:19.630
We know very little about him.

00:42:19.630 --> 00:42:23.410
I had to really work hard to
