00:42:23.410 --> 00:42:25.960
Interestingly enough he
appears in some histories

00:42:25.960 --> 00:42:28.820
as well as some archives.

00:42:28.820 --> 00:42:33.480 position:56%
Let me read to you what one witness,

00:42:33.480 --> 00:42:37.990
someone who knew Abu al-Qasim
Ramisht, how he described him.

00:42:37.990 --> 00:42:41.770
"Abu al-Qasim Ramisht was one
such wealthy man, a merchant,

00:42:41.770 --> 00:42:45.110
a tycoon, and a benefactor."

00:42:45.110 --> 00:42:49.640
A native of the province Fars which
lay in the South West part of Iran.

00:42:49.640 --> 00:42:54.290
He made his fortune
by trade and shipping,

00:42:54.290 --> 00:42:57.800
especially through
the port of Siraf.

00:42:57.800 --> 00:43:00.020
One observer has it
that Ramisht was one

00:43:00.020 --> 00:43:04.030
of Siraf's most wealthy
and celebrated men.

00:43:04.030 --> 00:43:07.050
I quote, "It's inhabitants
are very rich.

00:43:07.050 --> 00:43:10.320
I was told that one of them
feeling ill drew up his will,

00:43:10.320 --> 00:43:13.550
and a third part of his
fortune which he had in cash,

00:43:13.550 --> 00:43:16.760
amounted to a million gold
coins, not including the capital

00:43:16.760 --> 00:43:20.160
in which he laid out to
people who undertook to trade

00:43:20.160 --> 00:43:21.710
with it in a partnership."

00:43:21.710 --> 00:43:23.500
Those are technical terms actually,

00:43:23.500 --> 00:43:27.210
that partnership is a
financial arrangement,

00:43:27.210 --> 00:43:32.390
according to which Ramisht and his
colleagues pooled their capital

00:43:32.390 --> 00:43:37.460
and shared at least some of the
risk for long distance shipping.

00:43:37.460 --> 00:43:38.940
"Then there is Ramisht."

00:43:38.940 --> 00:43:46.670
The source continues, "whose son
Musa I met in Aden in year 539."

00:43:46.670 --> 00:43:50.590
Which corresponds to 1144, or 1145.

00:43:50.590 --> 00:43:53.580
"He told me that the
silver plate used by him,

00:43:53.580 --> 00:43:57.460
when weighed was found
to weigh about a ton.

00:43:57.460 --> 00:44:01.780
Musa is the youngest of his sons,
and he has the least merchandise.

00:44:01.780 --> 00:44:06.170
Ramisht himself has four
servants, each of whom is said

00:44:06.170 --> 00:44:08.230
to be richer than his son Musa.

00:44:08.230 --> 00:44:12.930
I met someone named Alia Nili
from the countryside of Hela."

00:44:12.930 --> 00:44:14.380
A town in Southern Iraq.

00:44:14.380 --> 00:44:17.540
"Who was Ramisht's clerk,
his secretary, and he told me

00:44:17.540 --> 00:44:21.860
that when he returned from China 20
years earlier his merchandise was

00:44:21.860 --> 00:44:24.100
worth half a million gold coins.

00:44:24.100 --> 00:44:29.230
If that's the wealth of the clerk,
what must Ramisht himself be worth?

00:44:29.230 --> 00:44:33.790
It was Ramisht who removed
the silver water spout Kaaba."

00:44:33.790 --> 00:44:38.260
The Kaaba as you know sits in the
middle of the sanctuary in Mecca.

00:44:38.260 --> 00:44:41.850
"Replacing it with a gold
one, and who draped the Kaaba

00:44:41.850 --> 00:44:47.660
in Chinese cloth whose
value is beyond estimate.

00:44:47.660 --> 00:44:49.950
In some I have heard
of no merchant nowadays

00:44:49.950 --> 00:44:52.440
who is equal Ramisht
in wealth or prestige."

00:44:52.440 --> 00:44:59.290
These were acts of conscientious,
he was showing off his wealth.

00:44:59.290 --> 00:45:03.900
He also established benefactions,
and sheltered his wealth.

00:45:03.900 --> 00:45:07.520
He made his wealth by
being just one example,

00:45:07.520 --> 00:45:13.600
and there would have been hundreds
indeed thousands of shippers,

00:45:13.600 --> 00:45:17.530
merchants, by extension
bankers because they lent money,

00:45:17.530 --> 00:45:19.720
who were part of a network of trade

00:45:19.720 --> 00:45:22.200
that connected the
Western Mediterranean

00:45:22.200 --> 00:45:27.530 position:56%
with the South Indian and China Sea.

00:45:27.530 --> 00:45:33.330
All of that trade was possible-
it was facilitated by capital,

00:45:33.330 --> 00:45:38.130
by legal instruments,
by coinage, by trust.

00:45:38.130 --> 00:45:42.880
In many respects, in fact many
historians have argued this,

00:45:42.880 --> 00:45:45.570
this was preindustrial capitalism.

00:45:45.570 --> 00:45:52.080
This was a form of
capitalism at work.

00:45:52.080 --> 00:45:55.730
A final example, and I'll end here.

00:45:55.730 --> 00:46:00.280
Islam and religious dogma.

00:46:00.280 --> 00:46:06.930
Islam we read more less constantly
as fettered by faith, irrational.

00:46:10.810 --> 00:46:16.690
My answer there of course is Ibn
Rushd, extraordinary philosopher.

00:46:16.690 --> 00:46:20.360
I mentioned Abu al-Qasim Ramisht
belongs to the 12th century,

00:46:20.360 --> 00:46:24.230
I've just stayed here in the
9th, 10th, 11th, 12th century,

00:46:24.230 --> 00:46:26.900
of course there other examples.

00:46:26.900 --> 00:46:31.320
The book begins with Muhammed and
ends in the early 16th century,

00:46:31.320 --> 00:46:33.410
but I'm sticking with
the 12th century.

00:46:33.410 --> 00:46:39.800
Ramisht was born Iran,
Arib was born in Iraq.

00:46:39.800 --> 00:46:44.760
Ibn Rushd or Averroes was born
in Cordoba, of course Spain

00:46:44.760 --> 00:46:48.160
in the 12th century was
part of the Islamic world.

00:46:48.160 --> 00:46:52.480
He was born into a very
distinguished family of jurists,

00:46:52.480 --> 00:46:58.760
of lawyers, but he clearly had had
from an early moment in his life,

00:46:58.760 --> 00:47:04.100
a disposition to asking
fundamental questions of the truth.

00:47:04.100 --> 00:47:07.590
How does one know things?

00:47:07.590 --> 00:47:12.770
What are the epistemological
basies upon which the law sits?

00:47:12.770 --> 00:47:15.830
How do I understand revelation?

00:47:15.830 --> 00:47:18.030
How do I understand truth?

00:47:18.030 --> 00:47:21.460
Those are not always
questions seek to answer.

00:47:21.460 --> 00:47:25.590
Lawyers like to find answers to
problems, either applied problems

00:47:25.590 --> 00:47:28.830
or theoretical problems as
thrown up by the law itself,

00:47:28.830 --> 00:47:31.260
not the underpinnings of the law.

00:47:31.260 --> 00:47:37.810 position:56%
At a young age he clearly manifested
an interest in that direction

00:47:37.810 --> 00:47:45.690
and he had the great good
fortune to run into a patron,

00:47:45.690 --> 00:47:53.520
a ruler who commissioned and
fueled his philosophical appetite.

00:47:53.520 --> 00:47:57.570
I'll read to you very
briefly the anecdote,

00:47:57.570 --> 00:48:03.930
which in many respects is the pivot
upon which Ibn Rushd's life swings.

00:48:03.930 --> 00:48:10.410
"When I entered into the
presence of the caliph Abu Ya'qub,

00:48:10.410 --> 00:48:14.700
I found him with someone named
Abu Bakr Ibn Tufayl alone."

00:48:14.700 --> 00:48:17.470
Ibn Tufayl was a philosopher
himself.

00:48:17.470 --> 00:48:21.300
"Abu Bakr Ibn Tufayl
began by praising me."

00:48:21.300 --> 00:48:24.610
This is Ibn Rushd speaking
in the first person.

00:48:24.610 --> 00:48:29.460
"Mentioning my family, and my
ancestors, and generously including

00:48:29.460 --> 00:48:33.120
in the recital achievements
well beyond my real merits,

00:48:33.120 --> 00:48:35.510 position:56%
he was flattering me in the presence

00:48:35.510 --> 00:48:41.350
of someone who's patronage he was
trying to arrange for Ibn Rushd.

00:48:41.350 --> 00:48:46.380
The first thing he said to me after
asking my name, my father's name,

00:48:46.380 --> 00:48:48.900
and my genealogy, his
bonafides, where do you from,

00:48:48.900 --> 00:48:52.190
are you come from a
good family or not?

00:48:52.190 --> 00:48:56.510
The first thing he asked me
was this, what is your opinion

00:48:56.510 --> 00:49:02.340
about the heavens referring to
the views of the philosophers.

00:49:02.340 --> 00:49:05.950
Are they eternal, or
are they created?"

00:49:05.950 --> 00:49:11.290
That's a fundamental question in
Islamic and premodern philosophy,

00:49:11.290 --> 00:49:17.310
is the world created,
or is it eternal?

00:49:19.480 --> 00:49:24.250
"Confusion and fear took hold of
me, and I began making excuses

00:49:24.250 --> 00:49:28.550
and denying that I'd ever concern
myself with philosophical learning.

00:49:28.550 --> 00:49:33.450
It was problematic to ask
these fundamental questions.

00:49:33.450 --> 00:49:36.870
For I did not know what
Ibn Tufayl had told him."

00:49:36.870 --> 00:49:43.560
In other words, his philosopher
companion had already the caliph

00:49:43.560 --> 00:49:45.630
to the idea that here
is a fellow philosopher

00:49:45.630 --> 00:49:48.060
who asks fundamental questions.

00:49:48.060 --> 00:49:50.600
Ibn Rushd didn't know that.

00:49:52.070 --> 00:49:54.780
"But the caliph understood
my fear and confusion,

00:49:54.780 --> 00:49:57.630
and turning to Ibn Tufayl began
talking about the question

00:49:57.630 --> 00:50:01.640
of which he had asked me,
mentioning what Aristotle, Plato,

00:50:01.640 --> 00:50:03.100
and all the philosophers had said,

00:50:03.100 --> 00:50:05.090
and bringing in beside
the objections

00:50:05.090 --> 00:50:07.210
of the Muslim thinkers
against them."

00:50:07.210 --> 00:50:08.510
What's the point here?

00:50:08.510 --> 00:50:15.740
If we think about our own
tradition, if we think about some

00:50:15.740 --> 00:50:21.900
of the categories of religion and
secular, we think about the rise

00:50:21.900 --> 00:50:26.600
of modern science in the
17th and 18th century.

00:50:26.600 --> 00:50:29.420
We don't think really
about Islamic learning.

00:50:29.420 --> 00:50:34.470
In fact Ibn Rushd is
a fascinating example

00:50:34.470 --> 00:50:42.470
in which hyper skepticism was cross
pollinating into Southern Europe.

00:50:42.470 --> 00:50:46.820
Ibn Rushd had more than a passing
acquaintance with Aristotle.

00:50:46.820 --> 00:50:52.070
Ibn Rushd, in fact wrote three
separate series of commentaries

00:50:52.070 --> 00:50:57.050 position:56%
on Aristotle, the last of which
deeply learned which were translated

00:50:57.050 --> 00:50:59.930
into Latin very quickly, and began

00:50:59.930 --> 00:51:06.260
to inform Christian European
learning in the 13th century.

00:51:06.260 --> 00:51:08.380
In fact there were
controversies in Paris,

00:51:08.380 --> 00:51:12.960
and other European cities
based on Ibn Rushd's ideas.

00:51:12.960 --> 00:51:15.690
And in fact historians of
the enlightenment will say

00:51:15.690 --> 00:51:22.900 position:56%
that there was an underground heresy
that is to say highly iconoclastic,

00:51:22.900 --> 00:51:28.080
highly skeptical views which passed
fundamental questions about God,

00:51:28.080 --> 00:51:32.000
and the world, which owe themselves

00:51:32.000 --> 00:51:34.940
to the Islamic philosophical
tradition, and particular

00:51:34.940 --> 00:51:38.300
to Ibn Rushd's contribution.

00:51:38.300 --> 00:51:46.250
"An underground intellectual
heresy" is as one scholar put it.

00:51:46.250 --> 00:51:50.370
13th, 14th, 15th century
Europe, the soil out of

00:51:50.370 --> 00:51:54.240
which our own tradition
grows that was mixed

00:51:54.240 --> 00:51:59.260
in with this Islamic
form of hyper skepticism.

00:51:59.260 --> 00:52:02.350
I could go on, but
I've run out of time.

00:52:02.350 --> 00:52:06.040
I hope I've given you some sense
of what I've tried to achieve

